1
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:24,033
l feel like you're driving me
to a court-martial.

2
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:26,037
This is crazy. What did I do?

3
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:27,513
I feel like you're going to pull over
and snuff me.

4
00:01:27,640 --> 00:01:29,915
What, you're not allowed to talk?
Hey, Forrest!

5
00:01:30,040 --> 00:01:31,155
We can talk, sir.

6
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:34,875
-Oh, I see. So it's personal?
-No, you intimidate them.

7
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:37,992
Good God, you're a woman.
I honestly... I couldn't have called that.

8
00:01:38,120 --> 00:01:40,429
I mean, I'd apologise,
but isn't that what we're going for here?

9
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:43,199
-I thought of you as a soldier first.
-I'm an airman.

10
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:44,958
You have, actually,
excellent bone structure, there.

11
00:01:45,080 --> 00:01:47,719
I'm kind of having a hard time
not looking at you now.

12
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:50,434
ls that weird? Come on, it's okay, laugh.

13
00:01:50,880 --> 00:01:53,235
-Sir, I have a question to ask.
-Yes, please.

14
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:56,875
ls it true you went 12 for 12
with last year's <i>Maxim</i> cover models?

15
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:58,991
That is an excellent question.
Yes and no.

16
00:01:59,120 --> 00:02:00,473
March and I had a scheduling conflict,

17
00:02:00,600 --> 00:02:03,353
but fortunately,
the Christmas cover was twins.

18
00:02:03,480 --> 00:02:06,199
Anything else? You're kidding me
with the hand up, right?

19
00:02:06,320 --> 00:02:09,995
-ls it cool if I take a picture with you?
-Yes. lt's very cool.

20
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:14,708
All right.

21
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:16,831
I don't want to see this
on your MySpace page.

22
00:02:16,960 --> 00:02:18,439
Please, no gang signs.

23
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:20,039
No, throw it up. I'm kidding.

24
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:22,958
Yeah, peace. I love peace.
I'd be out of a job with peace.

25
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:26,948
Come on. Hurry up. Just click it.
Don't change any settings. Just click it.

26
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:34,316
-What's going on?
-Contact left!

27
00:02:34,440 --> 00:02:35,998
What have we got?

28
00:02:37,240 --> 00:02:39,196
Jimmy, stay with Stark!

29
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:40,275
-Stay down!
-Yeah.

30
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:47,833
Son of a bitch!

31
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:52,113
-Wait, wait, wait! Give me a gun!
-Stay here!

32
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:21,474
Whoa!

33
00:04:08,960 --> 00:04:10,154
<i>Tony Stark.</i>

34
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:13,915
<i>Visionary. Genius.</i>

35
00:04:14,760 --> 00:04:16,557
<i>American patriot.</i>

36
00:04:16,680 --> 00:04:17,715
<i>Even from an early age,</i>

37
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:20,149
<i>the son of legendary</i>
<i>weapons developer Howard Stark</i>

38
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:23,670
<i>quickly stole the spotlight</i>
<i>with his brilliant and unique mind.</i>

39
00:04:23,800 --> 00:04:27,031
<i>At age four,</i>
<i>he built his first circuit board.</i>

40
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:29,196
<i>At age six, his first engine.</i>

41
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:33,509
<i>And at 17, he graduated</i>
<i>summa cum laude from MlT.</i>

42
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:36,755
<i>Then, the passing of a titan.</i>

43
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:41,073
<i>Howard Stark's lifelong friend</i>
<i>and ally, Obadiah Stane,</i>

44
00:04:41,200 --> 00:04:44,431
<i>steps in to help fill the gap</i>
<i>left by the legendary founder,</i>

45
00:04:44,680 --> 00:04:47,831
<i>until, at age 21, </i>
<i>the prodigal son returns</i>

46
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:51,157
<i>and is anointed the new CEO</i>
<i>of Stark lndustries.</i>

47
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:52,508
<i>With the keys to the kingdom,</i>

48
00:04:52,640 --> 00:04:55,279
<i>Tony ushers in a new era</i>
<i>for his father's legacy,</i>

49
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:59,234
<i>creating smarter weapons,</i>
<i>advanced robotics, satellite targeting.</i>

50
00:04:59,360 --> 00:05:03,035
<i>Today, Tony Stark has changed</i>
<i>the face of the weapons industry</i>

51
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:05,799
<i>by ensuring freedom</i>
<i>and protecting America</i>

52
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:08,309
<i>and her interests around the globe.</i>

53
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:18,555
<i>As liaison to Stark lndustries,</i>

54
00:05:19,200 --> 00:05:22,715
<i>l've had the unique privilege</i>
<i>of serving with a real patriot.</i>

55
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:26,390
<i>He is my friend</i>
<i>and he is my great mentor.</i>

56
00:05:26,920 --> 00:05:28,990
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, it is my honour</i>

57
00:05:29,120 --> 00:05:33,193
<i>to present this year's Apogee Award</i>
<i>to Mr Tony Stark.</i>

58
00:05:40,200 --> 00:05:41,394
<i>Tony?</i>

59
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:55,668
-Thank you, Colonel.
-Thanks for the save.

60
00:05:55,800 --> 00:05:59,270
<i>This is beautiful. Thank you.</i>
<i>Thank you all very much.</i>

61
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:00,753
<i>This is wonderful.</i>

62
00:06:02,600 --> 00:06:04,477
<i>Well, I'm not Tony Stark.</i>

63
00:06:06,320 --> 00:06:11,189
<i>But if I were Tony,</i>
<i>I would tell you how honoured I feel</i>

64
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:16,031
<i>and what a joy it is</i>
<i>to receive this very prestigious award.</i>

65
00:06:16,520 --> 00:06:17,839
<i>Tony, you know...</i>

66
00:06:17,960 --> 00:06:21,669
<i>The best thing about Tony</i>
<i>is also the worst thing.</i>

67
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:23,074
<i>He's always working.</i>

68
00:06:25,160 --> 00:06:28,357
Work it! Come on!

69
00:06:31,840 --> 00:06:35,196
-We should just stay till the morning.
-You are unbelievable.

70
00:06:35,320 --> 00:06:38,437
-Oh, no! Did they rope you into this?
-Nobody roped me into anything!

71
00:06:38,560 --> 00:06:39,515
-I'm so sorry.
-But they told me that

72
00:06:39,640 --> 00:06:42,279
if I presented you with an award,
you'd be deeply honoured.

73
00:06:42,400 --> 00:06:44,197
Of course I'd be deeply honoured.
And it's you, that's great.

74
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:45,912
-So when do we do it?
-lt's right here.

75
00:06:46,040 --> 00:06:48,076
-Here you go.
-There it is. That was easy.

76
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:49,428
-I'm so sorry.
-Yeah, it's okay.

77
00:06:49,560 --> 00:06:51,755
Wow! Would you look at that?
That's something else.

78
00:06:51,880 --> 00:06:53,359
I don't have any of those
floating around.

79
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:55,436
We're gonna let it ride!

80
00:06:56,520 --> 00:06:58,511
Give me a hand, will you?
Give me a little something-something.

81
00:06:58,640 --> 00:06:59,675
Okay, you, too.

82
00:06:59,800 --> 00:07:01,552
-I don't blow on a man's dice.
-Come on, honey bear.

83
00:07:01,680 --> 00:07:04,069
There it is.
Lieutenant Colonel Rhodes rolls! And...

84
00:07:04,200 --> 00:07:05,349
Two craps. Line away.

85
00:07:05,480 --> 00:07:07,152
-That's what happens.
-Worse things have happened.

86
00:07:07,280 --> 00:07:08,599
I think we're gonna be fine.
Colour me up, will you?

87
00:07:09,160 --> 00:07:10,115
-This is where I exit.
-All right.

88
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:11,195
Tomorrow, don't be late.

89
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:12,389
-Yeah, you can count on it.
-I'm serious!

90
00:07:12,520 --> 00:07:13,714
I know, I know.

91
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:17,196
Render unto Caesar
that which is Caesar's. There you go.

92
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:23,595
Mr Stark! Excuse me, Mr Stark!

93
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:26,076
Christine Everhart,
<i>Vanity Fair</i> magazine.

94
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:27,189
Can I ask you a couple of questions?

95
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:28,719
-She's cute.
-She's all right?

96
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:29,835
-Hi.
-Hi.

97
00:07:29,960 --> 00:07:31,757
-Yeah. Okay, go.
-lt's okay?

98
00:07:31,880 --> 00:07:33,552
You've been called
the da Vinci of our time.

99
00:07:33,680 --> 00:07:36,399
-What do you say to that?
-Absolutely ridiculous. I don't paint.

100
00:07:36,520 --> 00:07:37,999
And what do you say
to your other nickname?

101
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:39,189
"The Merchant of Death"?

102
00:07:39,320 --> 00:07:40,719
That's not bad.

103
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:44,477
-Let me guess. Berkeley?
-Brown, actually.

104
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:46,990
Well, Ms Brown,

105
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:49,431
it's an imperfect world,
but it's the only one we've got.

106
00:07:49,560 --> 00:07:52,120
I guarantee you, the day weapons are
no longer needed to keep the peace,

107
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,310
I'll start making bricks and beams
for baby hospitals.

108
00:07:54,440 --> 00:07:55,395
Rehearse that much?

109
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:57,078
Every night in front of the mirror
before bedtime.

110
00:07:57,200 --> 00:07:59,430
-I can see that.
-I'd like to show you first-hand.

111
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:01,676
All I want is a serious answer.

112
00:08:01,800 --> 00:08:03,870
Okay, here's serious.
My old man had a philosophy,

113
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,275
"Peace means having a bigger stick
than the other guy."

114
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:08,550
That's a great line
coming from the guy selling the sticks.

115
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:11,319
My father helped defeat the Nazis.
He worked on the Manhattan Project.

116
00:08:11,440 --> 00:08:13,874
A lot of people,
including your professors at Brown,

117
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:15,069
would call that being a hero.

118
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:17,236
And a lot of people
would also call that war profiteering.

119
00:08:17,360 --> 00:08:19,396
Tell me, do you plan to report
on the millions we've saved

120
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:21,158
by advancing medical technology

121
00:08:21,280 --> 00:08:23,475
or kept from starvation
with our intelli-crops?

122
00:08:23,600 --> 00:08:26,672
All those breakthroughs,
military funding, honey.

123
00:08:28,280 --> 00:08:30,032
You ever lose an hour of sleep
your whole life?

124
00:08:30,160 --> 00:08:31,957
I'd be prepared to lose a few with you.

125
00:08:45,600 --> 00:08:47,158
<i>Good morning. lt's 7:00 a.m.</i>

126
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:50,750
<i>The weather in Malibu</i>
<i>is 72 degrees with scattered clouds.</i>

127
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:54,117
<i>The surf conditions are fair</i>
<i>with waist-to-shoulder high lines.</i>

128
00:08:54,240 --> 00:08:56,549
<i>High tide will be at 10:52 a.m.</i>

129
00:09:12,920 --> 00:09:14,114
Tony?

130
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:16,794
Hey, Tony?

131
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:39,830
<i>You are not authorised</i>
<i>to access this area.</i>

132
00:09:40,040 --> 00:09:42,554
-Jesus.
-That's Jarvis. He runs the house.

133
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:45,594
l've got your clothes here.
They've been dry-cleaned and pressed,

134
00:09:45,720 --> 00:09:47,358
and there's a car waiting for you outside

135
00:09:47,480 --> 00:09:49,596
that will take you anywhere
you'd like to go.

136
00:09:49,960 --> 00:09:53,270
-You must be the famous Pepper Potts.
-lndeed I am.

137
00:09:54,840 --> 00:09:58,549
After all these years, Tony still has you
picking up the dry-cleaning.

138
00:09:58,680 --> 00:10:01,877
I do anything and everything
that Mr Stark requires,

139
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:04,639
including, occasionally,
taking out the trash.

140
00:10:04,760 --> 00:10:05,749
Will that be all?

141
00:10:22,040 --> 00:10:23,519
Give me an exploded view.

142
00:10:23,640 --> 00:10:26,712
<i>The compression in cylinder three</i>
<i>appears to be low.</i>

143
00:10:27,120 --> 00:10:28,314
Log that.

144
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:33,910
-I'm gonna try again, right now.
-Please don't turn down my music.

145
00:10:34,040 --> 00:10:34,995
I'll keep you posted.

146
00:10:35,120 --> 00:10:36,758
You are supposed to be
halfway around the world right now.

147
00:10:36,880 --> 00:10:39,075
-How'd she take it?
-Like a champ.

148
00:10:39,320 --> 00:10:40,639
Why are you trying to hustle me
out of here?

149
00:10:40,760 --> 00:10:42,352
Your flight was scheduled to leave
an hour and a half ago.

150
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:44,471
That's funny, I thought with it being
my plane and all,

151
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:46,033
that it would just wait for me
to get there.

152
00:10:46,160 --> 00:10:47,798
Tony, I need to speak to you
about a couple things

153
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:48,909
before I get you out of the door.

154
00:10:49,040 --> 00:10:51,190
Doesn't it kind of defeat the whole
purpose of having your own plane

155
00:10:51,320 --> 00:10:52,389
if it departs before you arrive?

156
00:10:52,520 --> 00:10:55,671
Larry called. He's got another buyer
for the Jackson Pollock in the wings.

157
00:10:55,800 --> 00:10:57,313
Do you want it? Yes or no.

158
00:10:57,440 --> 00:10:59,396
ls it a good representation
of his spring period?

159
00:11:00,200 --> 00:11:02,555
No. The Springs was actually
the neighbourhood in East Hampton

160
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:03,829
where he lived and worked,

161
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:05,393
-not "spring" like the season.
-So?

162
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:09,638
I think it's a fair example.
I think it's incredibly overpriced.

163
00:11:10,520 --> 00:11:12,954
I need it. Buy it. Store it.

164
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:16,154
Okay.
The MlT commencement speech...

165
00:11:16,280 --> 00:11:18,953
ls in June. Please, don't harangue me
about stuff that's way, way, down...

166
00:11:19,080 --> 00:11:21,196
They're haranguing me,
so I'm gonna say yes.

167
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,833
Deflect it and absorb it.
Don't transmit it back to me.

168
00:11:22,960 --> 00:11:24,234
I need you to sign this
before you get on the plane.

169
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:26,237
What are you trying to get rid of me for?
What, you got plans?

170
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:28,635
-As a matter of fact, I do.
-I don't like it when you have plans.

171
00:11:28,760 --> 00:11:30,716
I'm allowed to have plans
on my birthday.

172
00:11:30,840 --> 00:11:32,239
-lt's your birthday?
-Yes.

173
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:33,713
I knew that. Already?

174
00:11:33,840 --> 00:11:37,196
Yeah. lsn't that strange?
lt's the same day as last year.

175
00:11:38,120 --> 00:11:40,554
-Get yourself something nice from me.
-I already did.

176
00:11:40,680 --> 00:11:42,989
-And?
-lt was very nice.

177
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:46,351
-Yeah.
-Very tasteful. Thank you, Mr Stark.

178
00:11:47,080 --> 00:11:49,036
You're welcome, Miss Potts.

179
00:11:52,120 --> 00:11:53,075
Okay.

180
00:12:10,760 --> 00:12:14,116
You're good.
I thought I lost you back there.

181
00:12:14,760 --> 00:12:18,514
You did, sir.
I had to cut across Mulholland.

182
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:20,074
I got you. I got you.

183
00:12:20,200 --> 00:12:21,553
What's wrong with you?

184
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:23,079
-What?
-Three hours.

185
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:25,236
I got caught doing a piece
for <i>Vanity Fair.</i>

186
00:12:25,360 --> 00:12:27,191
For three hours. For three hours
you got me standing here.

187
00:12:27,320 --> 00:12:29,709
Waiting on you now. Let's go. Come on.

188
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:32,237
Wheels up! Rock and roll!

189
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,434
-What you reading, platypus?
-Nothing.

190
00:12:42,560 --> 00:12:44,630
Come on, sour patch. Don't be mad.

191
00:12:44,760 --> 00:12:47,354
I told you, I'm not mad.
I'm indifferent, okay?

192
00:12:47,480 --> 00:12:48,799
-I said I was sorry.
-Good morning, Mr Stark.

193
00:12:48,920 --> 00:12:49,989
You don't need to apologise to me.
I'm your man.

194
00:12:50,120 --> 00:12:51,109
Hi. I told him I was sorry, but he...

195
00:12:51,240 --> 00:12:52,468
-I'm just indifferent right now.
-Hot towel?

196
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:53,715
You don't respect yourself,

197
00:12:53,840 --> 00:12:55,068
-so I know you don't respect me.
-I respect you.

198
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:56,474
I'm just your babysitter.

199
00:12:56,600 --> 00:12:58,955
So, when you need
your diaper changed... Thank you.

200
00:12:59,080 --> 00:13:01,116
Let me know
and l'll get you a bottle, okay?

201
00:13:01,240 --> 00:13:02,798
Hey! Heat up the sake, will you?

202
00:13:02,920 --> 00:13:04,194
-Thanks for reminding me.
-No, I'm not talking...

203
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:05,958
We're not drinking.
We're working right now.

204
00:13:06,080 --> 00:13:08,355
-You can't have sashimi without sake.
-You are constitutionally

205
00:13:08,480 --> 00:13:09,833
incapable of being responsible.

206
00:13:09,960 --> 00:13:12,474
lt would be irresponsible not to drink.
I'm just talking about a nightcap.

207
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:13,589
Hot sake?

208
00:13:13,720 --> 00:13:16,837
-Yes, two, please.
-No. I'm not drinking. I don't want any.

209
00:13:16,960 --> 00:13:18,234
That's what I'm talking about.

210
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:21,238
When I get up in the morning
and I'm putting on my uniform,

211
00:13:21,360 --> 00:13:22,998
you know what I recognise?

212
00:13:23,120 --> 00:13:28,069
I see in that mirror that every person
that's got this uniform on got my back!

213
00:13:28,200 --> 00:13:30,760
Hey, you know what?
I'm not like you. I'm not cut out...

214
00:13:30,880 --> 00:13:33,792
No, no. You don't have to be like me!
But you're more than what you are.

215
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:35,672
Can you excuse me if
I'm a bit distracted here?

216
00:13:35,800 --> 00:13:38,678
No! You can't be distracted right now!
Listen to me!

217
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:55,675
General.

218
00:13:55,800 --> 00:13:59,156
Welcome, Mr Stark. We look forward
to your weapons presentation.

219
00:13:59,280 --> 00:14:00,235
Thanks.

220
00:14:02,040 --> 00:14:04,793
ls it better to be feared or respected?

221
00:14:04,960 --> 00:14:07,872
I say, is it too much to ask for both?

222
00:14:08,800 --> 00:14:11,598
With that in mind,
I humbly present the crown jewel

223
00:14:11,720 --> 00:14:13,392
of Stark lndustries' Freedom Line.

224
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:14,475
lt's the first missile system

225
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:17,273
to incorporate our proprietary
repulsor technology.

226
00:14:17,400 --> 00:14:21,154
They say the best weapon
is one you never have to fire.

227
00:14:21,280 --> 00:14:23,157
I respectfully disagree.

228
00:14:23,280 --> 00:14:27,068
I prefer the weapon
you only have to fire once.

229
00:14:27,400 --> 00:14:30,392
That's how Dad did it.
That's how America does it.

230
00:14:31,200 --> 00:14:33,191
And it's worked out pretty well so far.

231
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:34,548
Find an excuse

232
00:14:34,680 --> 00:14:37,831
to let one of these off the chain,
and I personally guarantee you

233
00:14:37,960 --> 00:14:41,270
the bad guys won't even want
to come out of their caves.

234
00:14:59,080 --> 00:15:02,629
For your consideration, the Jericho.

235
00:15:13,800 --> 00:15:14,755
I'll be throwing one of these in

236
00:15:14,880 --> 00:15:16,757
with every purchase
of 500 million or more.

237
00:15:16,880 --> 00:15:17,835
To peace!

238
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:21,431
<i>-Tony.</i>
-Obie, what are you doing up?

239
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:23,915
<i>I couldn't sleep till I found out</i>
<i>how it went. How'd it go?</i>

240
00:15:24,040 --> 00:15:25,758
lt went great. Looks like it's gonna be
an early Christmas.

241
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:29,555
<i>Hey! Way to go, my boy!</i>
<i>l'll see you tomorrow, yeah?</i>

242
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:31,033
Why aren't you wearing those pyjamas
I got you?

243
00:15:31,160 --> 00:15:32,639
<i>Good night, Tony.</i>

244
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:36,309
-Hey, Tony.
-I'm sorry, this is the "fun-vee."

245
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:38,271
The "hum-drum-vee" is back there.

246
00:15:38,400 --> 00:15:40,960
-Nice job.
-See you back at base.

247
00:16:45,240 --> 00:16:47,276
I wouldn't do that if I were you.

248
00:17:22,440 --> 00:17:24,078
What the hell did you do to me?

249
00:17:24,920 --> 00:17:26,353
What I did?

250
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:29,272
What I did is to save your life.

251
00:17:29,560 --> 00:17:33,030
I removed all the shrapnel I could,
but there's a lot left,

252
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:34,832
and it's headed into your atrial septum.

253
00:17:35,560 --> 00:17:37,232
Here, want to see?

254
00:17:37,960 --> 00:17:40,599
I have a souvenir. Take a look.

255
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:45,270
l've seen many wounds like that
in my village.

256
00:17:45,400 --> 00:17:47,675
We call them the walking dead

257
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:50,837
because it takes about a week
for the barbs to reach the vital organs.

258
00:17:50,960 --> 00:17:53,599
-What is this?
-That is an electromagnet,

259
00:17:54,360 --> 00:17:56,351
hooked up to a car battery,

260
00:17:56,480 --> 00:17:59,233
and it's keeping the shrapnel
from entering your heart.

261
00:18:07,200 --> 00:18:09,156
That's right. Smile.

262
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:14,753
We met once, you know,
at a technical conference in Bern.

263
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:17,709
-I don't remember.
-No, you wouldn't.

264
00:18:18,120 --> 00:18:20,998
If I had been that drunk,
I wouldn't have been able to stand,

265
00:18:21,120 --> 00:18:24,157
much less give a lecture
on integrated circuits.

266
00:18:24,280 --> 00:18:25,474
Where are we?

267
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:29,152
Come on, stand up. Stand up!

268
00:18:30,120 --> 00:18:32,031
Just do as I do.

269
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:34,711
Come on, put your hands up.

270
00:18:36,400 --> 00:18:37,753
Those are my guns.
How did they get my guns?

271
00:18:37,880 --> 00:18:40,155
Do you understand me? Do as I do.

272
00:18:59,800 --> 00:19:03,839
He says, "Welcome, Tony Stark,
the most famous mass murderer

273
00:19:03,960 --> 00:19:05,632
"in the history of America."

274
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:10,399
He is honoured.

275
00:19:12,840 --> 00:19:14,512
He wants you to build the missile.

276
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:18,075
The Jericho missile
that you demonstrated.

277
00:19:21,560 --> 00:19:22,629
This one.

278
00:19:27,560 --> 00:19:28,515
I refuse.

279
00:19:38,800 --> 00:19:39,755
<i>Tony!</i>

280
00:20:27,760 --> 00:20:29,955
He wants to know what you think.

281
00:20:30,920 --> 00:20:32,592
I think you got a lot of my weapons.

282
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:45,153
He says they have everything you need
to build the Jericho missile.

283
00:20:45,840 --> 00:20:47,796
He wants you to make
the list of materials.

284
00:20:50,960 --> 00:20:53,428
He says for you
to start working immediately,

285
00:20:53,560 --> 00:20:56,632
and when you're done,
he will set you free.

286
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:02,434
-No, he won't.
-No, he won't.

287
00:21:15,480 --> 00:21:17,948
I'm sure they're looking for you, Stark.

288
00:21:18,080 --> 00:21:20,992
But they will never find you
in these mountains.

289
00:21:22,600 --> 00:21:26,115
Look, what you just saw,

290
00:21:26,960 --> 00:21:28,916
that is your legacy, Stark.

291
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:33,711
Your life's work,
in the hands of those murderers.

292
00:21:33,840 --> 00:21:35,990
ls that how you want to go out?

293
00:21:36,560 --> 00:21:41,270
ls this the last act of defiance
of the great Tony Stark?

294
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:43,479
Or are you going to
do something about it?

295
00:21:43,600 --> 00:21:48,469
Why should I do anything?
They're going to kill me, you, either way.

296
00:21:48,600 --> 00:21:51,672
And if they don't,
I'll probably be dead in a week.

297
00:21:51,800 --> 00:21:53,028
Well, then,

298
00:21:53,680 --> 00:21:56,592
this is a very important week for you,
isn't it?

299
00:21:59,320 --> 00:22:02,630
If this is going to be my work station,
I want it well-lit. I want these up.

300
00:22:02,960 --> 00:22:05,793
I need welding gear.
I don't care if it's acetylene or propane.

301
00:22:05,920 --> 00:22:08,036
I need a soldering station. I need
helmets. I'm gonna need goggles.

302
00:22:08,160 --> 00:22:10,993
I would like a smelting cup.
I need two sets of precision tools.

303
00:22:23,840 --> 00:22:26,115
-How many languages do you speak?
-A lot.

304
00:22:26,240 --> 00:22:28,834
But apparently,
not enough for this place.

305
00:22:28,960 --> 00:22:30,871
They speak Arabic, Urdu,

306
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:34,197
Dari, Pashto, Mongolian,
Farsi, Russian.

307
00:22:35,360 --> 00:22:39,433
-Who are these people?
-They are your loyal customers, sir.

308
00:22:40,120 --> 00:22:42,031
They call themselves the Ten Rings.

309
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:52,473
You know, we might be more productive

310
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:55,239
if you include me
in the planning process.

311
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:05,590
Okay, we don't need this.

312
00:23:07,480 --> 00:23:08,833
What is that?

313
00:23:10,320 --> 00:23:12,515
That's palladium, 0.15 grammes.

314
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:16,431
We need at least 1 .6, so why don't
you go break down the other 1 1?

315
00:23:19,040 --> 00:23:20,837
What's he doing?

316
00:23:21,360 --> 00:23:22,634
Working.

317
00:23:32,360 --> 00:23:35,158
Careful.
Careful, we only get one shot at this.

318
00:23:35,280 --> 00:23:37,794
Relax. I have steady hands.

319
00:23:38,800 --> 00:23:41,155
Why do you think you're still alive?

320
00:23:47,240 --> 00:23:50,437
-What do I call you?
-My name is Yinsen.

321
00:23:50,960 --> 00:23:53,190
Yinsen. Nice to meet you.

322
00:23:54,080 --> 00:23:55,832
Nice to meet you, too.

323
00:24:34,280 --> 00:24:36,430
That doesn't look like a Jericho missile.

324
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:39,837
That's because
it's a miniaturised arc reactor.

325
00:24:40,200 --> 00:24:42,839
I got a big one
powering my factory at home.

326
00:24:43,160 --> 00:24:45,799
lt should keep the shrapnel
out of my heart.

327
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:47,478
But what could it generate?

328
00:24:47,600 --> 00:24:51,912
lf my math is right, and it always is,
three gigajoules per second.

329
00:24:52,400 --> 00:24:54,755
That could run your heart
for 50 lifetimes.

330
00:24:54,880 --> 00:24:57,792
Yeah. Or something big for 15 minutes.

331
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:09,637
-This is our ticket out of here.
-What is it?

332
00:25:11,120 --> 00:25:12,553
Flatten them out and look.

333
00:25:15,080 --> 00:25:16,035
Oh, wow.

334
00:25:18,960 --> 00:25:20,473
lmpressive.

335
00:25:45,520 --> 00:25:47,317
Good.

336
00:25:47,440 --> 00:25:49,954
Good roll. Good roll.

337
00:25:50,760 --> 00:25:52,512
You still haven't told me
where you're from.

338
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:55,279
I'm from a small town called Gulmira.

339
00:25:55,840 --> 00:25:58,673
-lt's actually a nice place.
-Got a family?

340
00:25:59,040 --> 00:26:03,192
Yes, and I will see them
when I leave here.

341
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:05,479
And you, Stark?

342
00:26:09,480 --> 00:26:11,550
-No.
-No?

343
00:26:13,320 --> 00:26:15,709
So you're a man who has everything

344
00:26:16,440 --> 00:26:17,714
and nothing.

345
00:27:01,520 --> 00:27:04,432
lt doesn't look anything like the picture.

346
00:27:04,560 --> 00:27:05,959
Maybe it's been modified.

347
00:27:06,080 --> 00:27:07,115
The tail is wrong.

348
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:08,195
lt's just backwards.

349
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:53,235
Relax.

350
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:04,070
The bow and arrow

351
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:06,919
once was the pinnacle
of weapons technology.

352
00:28:09,400 --> 00:28:11,675
lt allowed the great Genghis Khan

353
00:28:12,480 --> 00:28:15,313
to rule from the Pacific to the Ukraine.

354
00:28:15,920 --> 00:28:19,435
An empire twice the size
of Alexander the Great

355
00:28:20,600 --> 00:28:23,956
and four times
the size of the Roman Empire.

356
00:28:27,480 --> 00:28:28,708
But today,

357
00:28:29,560 --> 00:28:32,791
whoever holds the latest Stark weapons

358
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:35,592
rules these lands.

359
00:28:37,880 --> 00:28:39,108
And soon,

360
00:28:42,040 --> 00:28:43,632
it will be my turn.

361
00:28:56,320 --> 00:28:57,719
Why have you failed me?

362
00:28:58,600 --> 00:29:00,158
We're working.

363
00:29:00,640 --> 00:29:01,755
Diligently.

364
00:29:02,040 --> 00:29:03,678
I let you live.

365
00:29:05,960 --> 00:29:07,712
This is how you repay me?

366
00:29:08,400 --> 00:29:10,595
lt's very complex.

367
00:29:11,080 --> 00:29:13,196
He's trying very hard.

368
00:29:13,560 --> 00:29:14,515
On his knees.

369
00:29:19,080 --> 00:29:20,593
You think I'm a fool?

370
00:29:21,400 --> 00:29:22,594
I'll get the truth.

371
00:29:23,320 --> 00:29:24,548
We're both working.

372
00:29:31,800 --> 00:29:32,835
Open your mouth.

373
00:29:33,200 --> 00:29:34,155
What does he want?

374
00:29:34,400 --> 00:29:36,391
You think I'm a fool?

375
00:29:40,120 --> 00:29:41,553
What's going on?

376
00:29:42,080 --> 00:29:44,435
Tell me the truth.

377
00:29:44,640 --> 00:29:46,073
He's building your Jericho.

378
00:29:49,040 --> 00:29:51,315
What do you want? A delivery date?

379
00:29:58,360 --> 00:29:59,588
I need him.

380
00:30:01,720 --> 00:30:03,119
Good assistant.

381
00:30:07,800 --> 00:30:11,588
You have till tomorrow
to assemble my missile.

382
00:31:13,720 --> 00:31:15,995
Okay? Can you move?

383
00:31:16,520 --> 00:31:18,238
Okay, say it again.

384
00:31:18,360 --> 00:31:20,715
41 steps straight ahead. Then 16 steps,

385
00:31:20,840 --> 00:31:24,116
that's from the door,
fork right, 33 steps, turn right.

386
00:31:31,480 --> 00:31:32,708
Where is Stark?

387
00:31:33,520 --> 00:31:34,873
He was here a moment ago.

388
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:36,035
Go look for him.

389
00:31:50,840 --> 00:31:53,593
Yinsen! Yinsen! Stark!

390
00:31:54,080 --> 00:31:55,638
Say something.
Say something back to him.

391
00:31:55,760 --> 00:31:57,990
-He's speaking Hungarian. I don't...
-Then speak Hungarian.

392
00:31:58,120 --> 00:32:00,429
-Okay. I know.
-What do you know?

393
00:32:22,840 --> 00:32:24,831
-How'd that work?
-Oh, my goodness.

394
00:32:25,240 --> 00:32:26,798
-It worked all right.
-That's what I do.

395
00:32:26,920 --> 00:32:29,354
-Let me finish this.
-lnitialise the power sequence.

396
00:32:29,760 --> 00:32:30,715
Okay.

397
00:32:31,760 --> 00:32:32,875
-Now!
-Tell me. Tell me.

398
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:36,390
Function 1 1 .
Tell me when you see a progress bar.

399
00:32:36,840 --> 00:32:37,989
-lt should be up right now.
-Yes.

400
00:32:38,120 --> 00:32:39,155
Talk to me. Tell me when you see it.

401
00:32:39,280 --> 00:32:40,713
-I have it.
-Press Control "I".

402
00:32:40,840 --> 00:32:43,115
-"I." Got it.
-"I." "Enter." "I" and "Enter."

403
00:32:43,240 --> 00:32:44,878
Come over here and button me up.

404
00:32:47,800 --> 00:32:48,915
Okay. All right.

405
00:32:49,040 --> 00:32:50,268
Every other hex bolt.

406
00:32:50,400 --> 00:32:52,391
-They're coming!
-Nothing pretty, just get it done.

407
00:32:52,520 --> 00:32:53,794
-Just get it done.
-They're coming.

408
00:32:56,160 --> 00:32:58,310
Make sure the checkpoints are clear
before you follow me out, okay?

409
00:32:58,440 --> 00:33:00,078
We need more time.

410
00:33:01,240 --> 00:33:02,195
Hey,

411
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:06,117
-I'm gonna go buy you some time.
-Stick to the plan!

412
00:33:06,840 --> 00:33:08,114
Stick to the plan!

413
00:33:10,040 --> 00:33:11,155
Yinsen!

414
00:35:56,800 --> 00:35:59,109
-Yinsen!
-Watch out!

415
00:36:13,640 --> 00:36:14,709
Stark.

416
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:17,991
Come on. We got to go.

417
00:36:18,720 --> 00:36:21,473
Move for me, come on. We got a plan.
We're gonna stick to it.

418
00:36:21,600 --> 00:36:23,397
This was always the plan, Stark.

419
00:36:23,880 --> 00:36:25,871
Come on, you're gonna go
see your family. Get up.

420
00:36:27,360 --> 00:36:29,191
My family is dead.

421
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:32,116
I'm going to see them now, Stark.

422
00:36:34,520 --> 00:36:35,873
lt's okay.

423
00:36:37,880 --> 00:36:40,713
I want this. I want this.

424
00:36:46,520 --> 00:36:48,351
Thank you for saving me.

425
00:36:49,800 --> 00:36:53,588
Don't waste it. Don't waste your life.

426
00:37:31,080 --> 00:37:32,035
My turn.

427
00:39:11,360 --> 00:39:12,315
Not bad.

428
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:44,228
Hey!

429
00:40:05,960 --> 00:40:07,757
How was the "fun-vee"?

430
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:12,230
Next time, you ride with me, okay?

431
00:40:42,080 --> 00:40:43,752
Watch it, coming up here.

432
00:40:45,680 --> 00:40:48,638
Are you kidding me with this?
Get rid of them.

433
00:40:56,600 --> 00:40:59,797
Your eyes are red.
A few tears for your long-lost boss?

434
00:40:59,920 --> 00:41:04,277
-Tears of joy. I hate job hunting.
-Yeah, vacation's over.

435
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:07,035
Where to, sir?

436
00:41:07,160 --> 00:41:08,673
-Take us to the hospital, please, Happy.
-No.

437
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:09,789
No? Tony, you have to

438
00:41:09,920 --> 00:41:10,909
-go to the hospital.
-No is a complete answer.

439
00:41:11,040 --> 00:41:12,792
-The doctor has to look at you.
-I don't have to do anything.

440
00:41:12,920 --> 00:41:14,273
l've been in captivity for three months.

441
00:41:14,400 --> 00:41:17,949
There are two things I want to do.
I want an American cheeseburger,

442
00:41:18,080 --> 00:41:19,035
-and the other...
-That's enough of that.

443
00:41:19,160 --> 00:41:21,515
...is not what you think. I want you
to call for a press conference now.

444
00:41:21,640 --> 00:41:22,629
-Call for a press conference?
-Yeah.

445
00:41:22,760 --> 00:41:25,149
-What on earth for?
-Hogan, drive. Cheeseburger first.

446
00:41:37,160 --> 00:41:38,798
Look at this!

447
00:41:40,640 --> 00:41:41,709
Tony.

448
00:41:44,040 --> 00:41:46,713
-We were going to meet at the hospital.
-No, I'm fine.

449
00:41:46,840 --> 00:41:48,114
Look at you!

450
00:41:48,920 --> 00:41:51,150
-You had to have a burger, yeah?
-Well, come on.

451
00:41:51,280 --> 00:41:53,589
-You get me one of those?
-There's only one left. I need it.

452
00:41:56,480 --> 00:41:59,153
Hey, look who's here! Yeah!

453
00:42:04,320 --> 00:42:05,719
-Miss Potts?
-Yes.

454
00:42:05,840 --> 00:42:06,989
Can I speak to you for a moment?

455
00:42:07,120 --> 00:42:10,556
I'm not part of the press conference,
but it's about to begin right now.

456
00:42:10,680 --> 00:42:11,908
I'm not a reporter.

457
00:42:12,040 --> 00:42:13,359
I'm Agent Phil Coulson,

458
00:42:13,480 --> 00:42:15,118
with the Strategic Homeland
lntervention, Enforcement

459
00:42:15,240 --> 00:42:16,753
and Logistics Division.

460
00:42:16,880 --> 00:42:19,440
-That's quite a mouthful.
-I know. We're working on it.

461
00:42:19,560 --> 00:42:23,792
You know, we've been approached
already by the DOD, the FBl, the ClA...

462
00:42:23,920 --> 00:42:27,356
We're a separate division
with a more specific focus.

463
00:42:27,480 --> 00:42:30,995
We need to debrief Mr Stark
about the circumstances of his escape.

464
00:42:31,120 --> 00:42:34,192
-I'll put something in the book, shall I?
-Thank you.

465
00:42:38,880 --> 00:42:41,269
Hey, would it be all right
if everyone sat down?

466
00:42:41,400 --> 00:42:44,631
Why don't you just sit down?
That way you can see me, and I can...

467
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:46,836
A little less formal and...

468
00:42:51,520 --> 00:42:54,080
-What's up with the love-in?
-Don't look at me.

469
00:42:54,200 --> 00:42:56,111
I don't know what he's up to.

470
00:42:56,240 --> 00:42:58,515
-Good to see you.
-Good to see you.

471
00:42:58,640 --> 00:43:00,915
I never got to say goodbye to Dad.

472
00:43:01,200 --> 00:43:03,794
I never got to say goodbye to my father.

473
00:43:07,480 --> 00:43:08,674
There's questions
that I would have asked him.

474
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:11,678
I would have asked him how he felt
about what this company did.

475
00:43:13,120 --> 00:43:15,873
lf he was conflicted,
